arch:property.oc:show_val: Subsequent period of abandonment and debris accumulation following the temple's major collapse. Accumulated material include pottery (including fragments of Byzantine lamps), plaster, metal in a layer of yellowish-green clay material possibly associated with industrial reuse in the area.
Closing elevation: 905.576 m at northwest, 905.796 m at northeast, 905.636 m at southwest, 905.696 m at southeast, 905.616 m at center.
Phase XII: Use levels, robbing and abandonments continue.

This locus measures 5.66 m-x-3.10 m. This deposition layer of black-brown (5YR 3/2) soil has ash and charcoal bits over its surface. There are inclusions of yellow-green clay material recorded as well at the "Temple of the Winged Lions" as roof fall. This layer contains pottery, plaster, metal fragments, roof tiles, broken ashlar, tesserae and bone. This is the final deposition layer over the floor (Locus 22).
Phase XI: Further collapse post CE 5th c., possibly the result of the earthquake of CE 512. The east Porch columns and Central Arch collapse and fluvial deposits continue to accumulate.

Phase X: Site abandonment post major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c, Upper level robbing occurs including the upper treads of East and West Interior and Rear Staircases, and the associated upper landings. Evidence of squatter camps in the South Corridor and Central Arch.
Opening elevation: 905.856 m at northwest, 906.056 m at northeast, 905.756 m at southwest, 905.956 m at southeast, 905.606 m at center.
